	
                                                                                   PART 1: Node.js Fundamentals	
1.	Node.js is a JavaScript runtime that allows us to run JavaScript on the server. It is called a runtime because it executes JavaScript code outside the browser.
2.	Client-side JavaScript runs in the browser (e.g., form validation), while server-side JavaScript runs on the server (e.g., saving user data).
3.	Node.js Core Modules:
	http: Used to create a server
	fs: Used to read/write files
	path: Used to handle file paths
4.	Simple server: const http = require("http"); const server = http.createServer((req, res) => { res.end("Welcome to Wabiskill Family"); }); server.listen(3000);
5.	A port number is used to identify a server. If two applications use the same port, an error occurs.
6.	app.listen(5000, () => { console.log("Server running..."); }); This starts the server on port 7000 and prints a message.
      7. require() is used to import modules: const fs = require("fs");
      8. package.json is a file that stores project information and dependencies.
      9 .npm stands for Node Package Manager. It is used to install packages.
                                               PART 2: Express.js Fundamentals
    10. Express.js is a framework for Node.js that makes building servers easier.
  11. Steps:
	npm init -y
	npm install express
	Create server using express()
   12.GET route: app.get("/", (req, res) => { res.send("Hello Express"); });
   13.  Routing:
	GET: get data
	POST: send data
	PUT: update data
	DELETE: delete data
                                          PART 3: Middleware
   14. Middleware is a function that runs between request and response.
   15. Types of Middleware:
i.	Application-level
ii.	Router-level
iii.	Built-in
iv.	Error-handling
v.	Third-party
16 . Custom Middleware: app.use((req, res, next) => { console.log("Request received"); next(); });
17. If next() is not called, the request stops and the page does not load.
18. app.use(express.json()) is used to read JSON data from requests.
19. Middleware is a function, while JSON is a data format.
                                             PART 4: Backend & API Development
20. JSON is a data format used to store and transfer data: { "name": "Ali" }
21. req contains request data, res is used to send response.
22. res.send() sends text/HTML, res.json() sends JSON.
23.const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000; This uses environment port or default 3000.
24. Event Loop allows Node.js to handle multiple requests efficiently (non-blocking).
                              Final Challenge:
const express = require("express"); const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
app.use((req, res, next) => { console.log(req.method, req.url); next(); });
app.get("/", (req, res) => { res.send("Home"); });
app.get("/about", (req, res) => { res.send("About"); });
app.post("/login", (req, res) => { res.json({ message: "Login success" }); });
app.listen(4000);

